# Example System Prompts

This directory contains ready-to-use Markdown overlays that demonstrate how Codex Agentic stitches
custom system prompts into the runtime.

## Folder layout

```
example-system-prompts/
├── agentic-default.md      # baseline overlay shipped with the template
├── agent-codex.md          # sample customization layered on top of the default
└── README                  # this guide
```

Each `*.md` file represents a standalone overlay. At launch, Codex Agentic concatenates the files
located in `.codex/.custom-system-prompts/` (lexicographically) and appends the merged text to the
upstream base instructions.

## Using the examples

1. Ensure the repository root contains this folder (`openai-codex/example-system-prompts`).
2. Copy or symlink any subset of the Markdown files into `.codex/.custom-system-prompts/`:
   ```bash
   mkdir -p .codex/.custom-system-prompts
   cp example-system-prompts/agentic-default.md .codex/.custom-system-prompts/
   cp example-system-prompts/agent-codex.md .codex/.custom-system-prompts/
   ```
3. Launch the CLI/TUI (`cargo run --bin codex-agentic` or `./target/debug/codex-agentic`). The
   `/status` command will list the loaded prompt files.
4. Modify or duplicate the templates to create bespoke overlays. The loader only reads `*.md` files;
   other extensions (for example `notes.md.disabled`) are ignored.

## Tips

- Keep overlays focused on project-specific guidance (tooling, style rules, etc.).
- To disable an overlay temporarily, rename it to end with a non-`.md` suffix (e.g. `.md.disabled`).
- Commit shared overlays in `example-system-prompts/`; copy only the active subset into
  `.codex/.custom-system-prompts/` so developers can opt-in locally.
